---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Gravitational Microlensing - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Gravitational Microlensing</h1>
        
        <div class="infobox">
            <h3 class="infobox-title">Gravitational Microlensing</h3>
            <table>
                <tr>
                    <th>Type:</th>
                    <td>Gravitational lensing effect</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Scale:</th>
                    <td>μas to mas</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Timescale:</th>
                    <td>Days to years</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Applications:</th>
                    <td>Exoplanet detection<br>
                        Dark matter<br>
                        Stellar masses</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                    <th>Related:</th>
                    <td><WikiLink slug="pages/Gravitational_Lensing" text="Gravitational Lensing" /><br>
                        <WikiLink slug="pages/Einstein_Ring" text="Einstein Ring" /></td>
                </tr>
            </table>
        </div>

        <p><strong>Gravitational microlensing</strong> occurs when a massive object (the "lens") passes between an observer and a background star (the "source"), causing a transient brightening and astrometric shift of the source. Unlike <WikiLink slug="pages/Strong_Lensing" text="strong lensing" />, microlensing typically produces unresolved images and is detected through time-variable magnification.</p>

        <h2 id="section-0">Physical Principles</h2>
        
        <h3>Einstein Ring Radius</h3>
        <p>The fundamental scale of microlensing is the angular Einstein ring radius:<sup>[3]</sup></p>
        
        <p style="text-align: center;">θ<sub>E</sub> = √(κM<sub>l</sub>π<sub>rel</sub>)</p>
        
        <p>where:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>κ = 8.144 mas M<sub>⊙</sub><sup>-1</sup> (constant)</li>
            <li>M<sub>l</sub> = lens mass</li>
            <li>π<sub>rel</sub> = relative lens-source parallax</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Event Timescale</h3>
        <p>The Einstein crossing time characterizes event duration:</p>
        
        <p style="text-align: center;">t<sub>E</sub> = θ<sub>E</sub>/μ<sub>rel</sub></p>
        
        <p>where μ<sub>rel</sub> is the lens-source relative proper motion.</p>

        <h2 id="section-1">Applications</h2>

        <h3>Exoplanet Detection</h3>
        <p>Microlensing is uniquely sensitive to:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Cool planets beyond the snow line</li>
            <li>Low-mass planets down to Earth-mass</li>
            <li>Free-floating planets<sup>[3]</sup></li>
            <li>Planets around dim or dark hosts</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Dark Matter Searches</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>MACHOs (Massive Compact Halo Objects)</li>
            <li>Primordial black holes</li>
            <li>Dark stellar remnants</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Galactic Structure</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Stellar mass function</li>
            <li>Binary fraction</li>
            <li>Galactic bar properties</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-2">Surveys</h2>

        <h3>Current/Past Surveys</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>OGLE</strong> (Optical Gravitational Lensing Experiment)</li>
            <li><strong>MOA</strong> (Microlensing Observations in Astrophysics)</li>
            <li><strong>KMTNet</strong> (Korea Microlensing Telescope Network)</li>
            <li><strong>UKIRT</strong> microlensing survey</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Future: Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope</h3>
        <p>The <WikiLink slug="pages/Nancy_Grace_Roman_Space_Telescope" text="Roman" /> Galactic Bulge Time Domain Survey (GBTDS) will revolutionize microlensing:<sup>[3]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>~27,000 microlensing events expected</li>
            <li>~1,400 planet detections (0.1-10⁴ M<sub>⊕</sub>)</li>
            <li>~250 free-floating planets</li>
            <li>12.1-minute cadence in F146 filter</li>
            <li>1.4 sq. deg. lower bulge + 0.28 sq. deg. Galactic center</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-3">Observational Signatures</h2>

        <h3>Photometric</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Symmetric light curve (single lens)</li>
            <li>Achromatic brightening</li>
            <li>Unique shape: no repeat events</li>
            <li>Planetary anomalies: caustic crossings</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Astrometric</h3>
        <ul>
            <li>Centroid shift during event</li>
            <li>Breaks mass-distance degeneracy</li>
            <li>Requires high precision (μas level)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-4">Degeneracies and Solutions</h2>

        <p>From photometry alone, mass and distance are degenerate. Breaking methods include:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Microlensing parallax (Earth's orbital motion)</li>
            <li>Astrometric microlensing</li>
            <li>Lens flux detection</li>
            <li>Galactic model priors<sup>[3]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-5">Galactic Modeling</h2>

        <p>Accurate Galactic models are crucial for:<sup>[3]</sup></p>
        <ul>
            <li>Survey optimization</li>
            <li>Event rate predictions</li>
            <li>Mass-distance priors</li>
            <li>Detection efficiency calculations</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="evidence-for">
            <h4>Recent Model Improvements</h4>
            <p>The SP-H25 model for Roman GBTDS includes:<sup>[3]</sup></p>
            <ul>
                <li>Updated bulge density (Cao et al. 2013)</li>
                <li>Detailed disk kinematics (Koshimoto et al. 2021)</li>
                <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Nuclear_Stellar_Disk" text="Nuclear Stellar Disk" /> component</li>
                <li>Improved extinction modeling</li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <h2 id="section-6">Event Rates</h2>

        <p>Microlensing optical depth and event rates depend on:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Stellar density along line of sight</li>
            <li>Relative velocities (lens-source)</li>
            <li>Mass function</li>
            <li>Extinction (affects detection)</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Peak rates occur toward the Galactic bulge where stellar density is highest.</p>

        <h2 id="section-7">Challenges</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Rare events requiring continuous monitoring</li>
            <li>Crowded fields in Galactic bulge</li>
            <li>High extinction near Galactic plane</li>
            <li>Model uncertainties at |b| &lt; 0.5°<sup>[3]</sup></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-8">Future Prospects</h2>

        <ul>
            <li>Roman will increase planet yield by ~100×</li>
            <li>Mass measurements for thousands of lenses</li>
            <li>Free-floating planet census</li>
            <li>Improved Galactic structure constraints</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-9">See Also</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Gravitational_Lensing" text="Gravitational Lensing" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Exoplanet_Detection_Methods" text="Exoplanet Detection Methods" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Galactic_Bulge" text="Galactic Bulge" /></li>
            <li><WikiLink slug="pages/Nancy_Grace_Roman_Space_Telescope" text="Nancy Grace Roman Space Telescope" /></li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="section-10">References</h2>
        <ol class="references">
            <li>Paczynski, B. (1986) - "Gravitational microlensing by the galactic halo"</li>
            <li>Mao, S. (2012) - "Astrophysical applications of gravitational microlensing"</li>
            <li>Huston et al. (2026) - "An Updated SynthPop Model for Microlensing Simulations I" arXiv:2603.12219</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="page-tags">
            <strong>Tags:</strong>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Observational_Techniques" text="Observational Techniques" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Exoplanets" text="Exoplanets" />
            <WikiLink slug="pages/Tag_Galactic_Structure" text="Galactic Structure" />
        </div>
  </main>
</Base>
